<LENGTH>
<P>
448 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: DREAM HOUSE CAN IRON OUT HASSLES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Family Circle magazine recently surveyed 22 million female readers to find out 
what features they wanted most in a dream house. Their ideas are incorporated 
in a house being built in suburban Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
Most of the things the women suggested, I held out for in a home we built seven 
years ago. Our utility room is not off the kitchen; it's near the bedrooms so I 
can "dunk shot" my sheets into the washer. There is a walk-in pantry where you 
walk in at your own risk, but my kitchen looks great. No doors cover my 
cabinets. I always felt like a game contestant standing in front of my old 
ones, wondering which door held the brown sugar and which one the ant traps. 
</P>
<P>
There are no draperies in the house and no shower curtains. All I ever did 
anyway was to cut off the mildew periodically until all I had was a valance. 
</P>
<P>
My ironing board is attached to the wall of the utility room and is up all the 
time. This way I can tell people, "I'd take my ironing board down, but it's 
attached to the wall." 
</P>
<P>
I had a greenhouse window installed in the kitchen for "sick" plants that need 
TLC and more sun. It holds every live plant in the house. 
</P>
<P>
Sounds like an enchanted cottage, doesn't it? Wrong! 
</P>
<P>
Given a second chance, I'd make a lot of major changes. I don't mean just the 
doggie door we cut through an eight-inch wall and the dog ran away from home. I 
mean more technology. 
</P>
<P>
The kitchen table would go. In its place I'd have a trough centered over a 
drain that you would just hose down between meals. 
</P>
<P>
I'd install a conveyor belt from the garage to the pantry so I'd never again 
have to make eight trips on grocery day. 
</P>
<P>
There would be a timer in the bathroom; at the end of an hour, the water would 
shut off, the lights, blow dryers and curling irons would go dead, and the door 
would swing open. 
</P>
<P>
I haven't worked out all the bugs on this one, but I'd like a chute off the 
utility room for hand-washables. Anything left in the chute for three years 
would drop into a compost, and when broken down with a chemical, would turn 
into mulch for roses. 
</P>
<P>
The trouble with most homes is that men design them and women clean them. I'll 
never forget the first time I visited Monticello, the Virginia home of Thomas 
Jefferson. The greatest statesman of all time, who had one of the most creative 
minds in the world, was a do-it-your-selfer. He introduced bunk beds to America 
(did God give us orangutan arms?), a dumbwaiter for wine (the food came from a 
kitchen a mile away), and just inside the hallway, he built a clock that 
measured time by a weight that went down the other side of the door. There is a 
hole in the floor because he misjudged the minutes. 
</P>
<P>
I'm years ahead of my time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021190-0017 </DOCNO>
