<HEADLINE>
<P>
MALATHION CONTROVERSY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Why the need to protect the agricultural business of Southern California with 
malathion spraying? The land developers of Southern California have already 
launched their own Medfly assault, and it is clean and profitable. 
</P>
<P>
They simply bulldoze thousands of acres of producing orchards for future 
transportation corridors and housing developments. You don't need an MBA degree 
to figure out that the law of supply and demand will raise fruit prices, not 
the Medfly. The less fruit produced per capita in California will result in 
increased imports. So why the fuss? 
</P>
<P>
MARY SCHWARTZ 
</P>
<P>
Santa Ana 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021190-0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 174713 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 11, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 6; Column 6; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
319 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA MONICA MOUNTAINS PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the author of the 1978 legislation that created the Santa Monica Mountains 
National Recreation Area, I take issue with Bill Boyarsky's discouraging 
assessment of the efforts to save this beautiful area ("Watching the Mountains 
Go Downhill," Metro, Feb. 2). 
</P>
<P>
It's true that some very valuable pieces of land in the Santa Monicas have been 
lost to development, or are about to be. However, of the 150,000 acres within 
the boundaries of the recreation area, roughly 60,000 are already in public 
ownership -- thanks mainly to the state's foresight in establishing four large 
parks in the mountains many years ago. The 16,000 acres of park land Boyarsky 
mentioned refer only to land which the National Park Service itself has 
acquired. 
</P>
<P>
That the Park Service has been able to acquire even that much acreage is a 
testament to park supporters' ability to make progress under adverse 
circumstances. Not only did we have to contend with skyrocketing land prices 
and competition from developers, but also the opposition of President Reagan 
and his appointees. 
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, we were able to persuade Congress to continue appropriating at 
least modest amounts of funds for the Santa Monicas anyway, which enabled the 
National Park Service to buy some key properties. And, two years ago, the park 
got a big boost from Prop. 70, which provided $30 million for state 
acquisitions in the mountains. Now that we have a President who supports the 
Santa Monica Mountains park, the prospects for its continued expansion are more 
encouraging. 
</P>
<P>
We shall keep working to obtain federal funds for land acquisition but, to 
ensure that the Park Service has the opportunity to buy land before it is 
developed, local officials will need to make appropriate land-use decisions -- 
for example, refraining from increasing zoning densities, which make the land 
more attractive to develop. 
</P>
<P>
REP. ANTHONY C. 
</P>
<P>
BEILENSON 
</P>
