<HEADLINE>
<P>
CESAREAN FIGURES ON HOSPITAL TRANSFERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I was very interested to read the article about birthing centers gaining in 
popularity. I believe, however, the comments that 20% of all women develop 
complications, thus leading to a transfer and Cesarean section, are misleading. 
</P>
<P>
In a study on the safety of birthing centers (Dec. 28, the New England Journal 
of Medicine) the total transfer rate was 15.8%, but the total Cesarean rate was 
only 4.4%. 
</P>
<P>
The use of unnecessary interventions and misused technology caused 
complications leading to a Cesarean section for the birth of my first child. 
When pregnant a second time, I traveled over an hour to give birth naturally 
with no interventions. In the United States, the Cesarean rate can reach higher 
than 35% in some hospitals. Perhaps this trend toward out-of-hospital births 
can reduce Cesareans to a normal and acceptable rate. 
</P>
<P>
VICKY ORTEGA 
</P>
<P>
San Juan Capistrano 
</P>
</TEXT>
