188 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPECIAL REPORT: OIL ON THE BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
BIRDS IN PERIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Rick Vanderknyff. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Here are descriptions of five birds threatened by the oil spill off Huntington 
Beach, shown above from left. 
</P>
<P>
Western grebe (Aechmophorus occidentalis) 
</P>
<P>
Because it spends most of its time on the surface of coastal waters, this 
wintering bird is among the most vulnerable to the early effects of a spill. 
</P>
<P>
California least tern (Sterna antillarum browni) 
</P>
<P>
This endangered gull-like bird nests on the sand in wetlands such as Bolsa 
Chica. Now wintering farther south, its nesting grounds would be threatened if 
oil enters the wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
Brown pelican (Pelecanus occidentalis) 
</P>
<P>
This endangered bird flies along the surface and dives for fish; at least two 
have been found with their feathers covered with oil. 
</P>
<P>
Common murre (Uria aalge) 
</P>
<P>
Like the grebe, this sea bird bobs on the water's surface, diving occasionally 
for fish. 
</P>
<P>
Light-footed clapper rail (Rallus longirostris levipes) 
</P>
<P>
More than half of the state's population of this sedentary marsh bird lives in 
the dense cordgrass stands of Upper Newport Bay. Any damage to this nesting 
site would be devastating to the bird's future prospects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Western grebe (Aechmophorus occidentalis), Russ Arasmith ; Drawing, 
California least tern (Sterna antillarum browni), Russ Arasmith ; Drawing, 
Brown pelican (Pelecanus occidentalis), Russ Arasmith ; Drawing, Common murre 
(Uria aalge), Russ Arasmith ; Drawing, Light-footed clapper rail (Rallus 
longirostris levipes), Russ Arasmith 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
